item.description:
My preferred way of indentation is wrap-all, indent-by-one, which looks like:
// method call foo( param1, param2, param3, param4); // method declaration public void foo( String param1, String param2, String param3, String param4) { // implementation } (Pretend that the lines were long enough to need wrapping.)
&ldquo;wrap-all&rdquo; means, if a line passes the max line length (e.g. 120), don&rsquo;t just break it into only two lines, but wrap each segment of the method call/method declaration on it&rsquo;s own line, even if this creates more lines than necessary.

Joist 1.4.x got a new feature, Unit of Work snapshots, which I think are a neat way to handle a particular use-case that sometimes the chattiness of ORMs doesn&rsquo;t handle well.
The Use Case Specifically, I worked on an enterprise system once that had a fairly common pattern of:
// as part of the nightly batch cycle for (Integer parentId : allParentIds) { for (Integer childId : loadParent(parentId).

Stylistic tangent, because, hey, that&rsquo;s what I do; this is currently (A):
{code} if (condition) { // main logic // several lines // etc. } else { log.error(&ldquo;condition was bad&rdquo;); } {code}
Where as the alternatives are (B):
{code} if (!condition) { log.error(&ldquo;condition was bad&rdquo;) } else { // main logic // several lines // etc. } {code}
Or (C):
{code} if (!condition) { log.error(&ldquo;condition was bad&rdquo;) return } // main logic // several lines // etc.
